    "projects": [
        {
            "title": "Master's thesis - Chromatic k-Nearest Neighbors Queries using (Near-)Linear space",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 11,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2020
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 6,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2021
                }
            },
            "description": "For my master's thesis I have researched the chromatic k-nearest neighbors problem. This problem is the geometric interpretation of the k-nearest neighbors classifier from machine learning. In the problem, we want to build a data structure on a set of colored points, such that given a query point q, the most frequently occurring color among the k-nearest neighbors of q can be found efficiently.\nThe thesis contains results for this problem under the L_1, L_2 and L_infty metrics, in one and two dimension(s), though the results can likely be generalized to other metrics and higher dimensions with already existing results.\nAside from data structures for the regular problem, the thesis contains semi-online data structures (dynamic data structures, in which we know the time at which a point is deleted), as well as approximation data structures, that report a color that occurs often enough.\nThe data structures have all been analyzed in terms of their asymptotic complexities (preprocessing time, space and query time). While the complexities of the standard data structures are on the high end, the approxiation data structures perform very well, achieving (near-)linear space, coupled with a query times that are almost O(sqrt(n)).",
